  ('standing-cable-or-band-hip-flexion', 'Strengthens active chamber height and repeatability instead of relying only on passive hip range or momentum. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Strengthens active chamber height and repeatability instead of relying only on passive hip range or momentum.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the exercise builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve through progressive loading or leverage.', 'Use after skill and output priorities. Pair with enough rest that strength and position quality remain the target.', 'Do not chase load at the expense of joint position, support-leg alignment, or trunk control. Strength only transfers if the athlete owns the shape.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('landmine-rotational-press', 'Loads rotational force transfer through the foot, hip, trunk, and shoulder, useful for athletes who kick while punching, framing, or bracing against contact. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Loads rotational force transfer through the foot, hip, trunk, and shoulder, useful for athletes who kick while punching, framing, or bracing against contact.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the exercise builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve through progressive loading or leverage.', 'Use after skill and output priorities. Pair with enough rest that strength and position quality remain the target.', 'Do not chase load at the expense of joint position, support-leg alignment, or trunk control. Strength only transfers if the athlete owns the shape.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('pallof-press-with-march', 'Builds trunk stiffness against rotation while the legs move, a direct need for support-leg control during kicking and ball striking. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds trunk stiffness against rotation while the legs move, a direct need for support-leg control during kicking and ball striking.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the exercise builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve through progressive loading or leverage.', 'Use after skill and output priorities. Pair with enough rest that strength and position quality remain the target.', 'Do not chase load at the expense of joint position, support-leg alignment, or trunk control. Strength only transfers if the athlete owns the shape.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('heavy-sled-push', 'Builds concentric projection strength for entries, approaches, and short accelerations without the eccentric soreness of heavy sprint volume. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds concentric projection strength for entries, approaches, and short accelerations without the eccentric soreness of heavy sprint volume.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the exercise builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve through progressive loading or leverage.', 'Use after skill and output priorities. Pair with enough rest that strength and position quality remain the target.', 'Do not chase load at the expense of joint position, support-leg alignment, or trunk control. Strength only transfers if the athlete owns the shape.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('lateral-lunge-decel-stick', 'Builds the braking qualities needed when a kick misses, lands awkwardly, or must transition immediately into defense or a cut. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds the braking qualities needed when a kick misses, lands awkwardly, or must transition immediately into defense or a cut.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('kick-to-landing-stick', 'Makes the athlete finish the kick in a safe usable stance rather than only judging the strike by contact or speed. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Makes the athlete finish the kick in a safe usable stance rather than only judging the strike by contact or speed.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('eccentric-adductor-slider', 'Progressively loads the groin in the lengthening direction that matters for high kicks, side reaches, ball striking, and lateral recovery. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Progressively loads the groin in the lengthening direction that matters for high kicks, side reaches, ball striking, and lateral recovery.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('assisted-nordic-hamstring-eccentric', 'Builds hamstring tolerance for fast leg swing, recoil, sprint approach, and deceleration demands common in soccer and combat sports. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds hamstring tolerance for fast leg swing, recoil, sprint approach, and deceleration demands common in soccer and combat sports.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('tibialis-raise-kicking', 'Strengthens the anterior lower leg for repeated foot lifting, deceleration, checking, and striking positions that can stress the shins and ankles. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Strengthens the anterior lower leg for repeated foot lifting, deceleration, checking, and striking positions that can stress the shins and ankles.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('bent-knee-soleus-raise-kicking', 'Builds the lower-leg endurance and stiffness needed for bounce stance, repeated plants, pivots, and late-session kicking volume. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds the lower-leg endurance and stiffness needed for bounce stance, repeated plants, pivots, and late-session kicking volume.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('partner-low-kick-check-perturbation', 'Teaches the athlete to receive light, agreed contact in a check position without losing posture, balance, or partner communication. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Teaches the athlete to receive light, agreed contact in a check position without losing posture, balance, or partner communication.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds braking, landing, eccentric tolerance, trunk control, joint ownership, contact recovery, or tissue durability rather than max speed or conditioning.', 'Use after access, skill, output, and main strength priorities. Keep the drill controlled and quality-gated.', 'Do not surprise the athlete, overload end range, or punish them with sloppy fatigue reps. Resilience is controlled exposure, not chaos.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('repeat-kick-interval', 'Builds the ability to repeat technically useful kicks under fatigue while preserving recoil, stance, and defensive readiness. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Builds the ability to repeat technically useful kicks under fatigue while preserving recoil, stance, and defensive readiness.', 'Belongs in Sustained Capacity because the intended stress is repeating useful kicking or movement work under fatigue while maintaining posture, mechanics, spacing, and safety.', 'Use late in the session after skill, speed, power, and main strength work. Fatigue is part of the method, but mechanics set the cap.', 'Do not place this before technical learning or output. Do not reward exhausted sloppy kicks; quality gates decide the interval.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('shuttle-to-kick-conditioning', 'Conditions the sport sequence of moving, braking, striking, and recovering without pretending that tired sloppy kicks are better training. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Conditions the sport sequence of moving, braking, striking, and recovering without pretending that tired sloppy kicks are better training.', 'Belongs in Sustained Capacity because the intended stress is repeating useful kicking or movement work under fatigue while maintaining posture, mechanics, spacing, and safety.', 'Use late in the session after skill, speed, power, and main strength work. Fatigue is part of the method, but mechanics set the cap.', 'Do not place this before technical learning or output. Do not reward exhausted sloppy kicks; quality gates decide the interval.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.'),
  ('9090-breathing-with-hip-reset', 'Downshifts the athlete after kicking volume and helps recover hip, pelvis, and rib position without adding more training stress. Kicking athletes need the swing leg, stance leg, trunk, and foot to solve a shared timing problem: create range or force, transfer it through the hip and trunk, contact the target or ball, and recover to stance. This drill isolates one link without losing the sport relationship.', 'Downshifts the athlete after kicking volume and helps recover hip, pelvis, and rib position without adding more training stress.', 'Belongs in Restore because the goal is to downshift the nervous system, restore breathing, reduce tension, recover range, and support readiness without adding new stress.', 'Use at the end of the session only, after kicking, conditioning, strength, or sparring work is complete.', 'Do not make this aggressive stretching, extra conditioning, or skill practice. The athlete should leave calmer and less guarded.', 'Scale by reducing range, speed, load, reaction choices, partner pressure, impact, or total volume first. Progress only one variable at a time and only after the athlete owns the quality gate.')
